<div id="review_877811778" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/877811778" />
    <a title="Sudha Kuruganti" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28788613-sudha-kuruganti"><img alt="Sudha Kuruganti" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1458073750p2/28788613.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/877811778?book_show_action=true">Mar 10, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sudha Kuruganti" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sudha Kuruganti" href="/user/show/28788613-sudha-kuruganti">Sudha Kuruganti</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28788613-sudha-kuruganti?shelf=south-asian-writers">south-asian-writers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer877811778" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer730592372500634782">Just a few pages into this book, I&apos;d already decided that I liked the heroine, Rumi, a lot. Mainly because I love seeing <i>intelligent</i>, mature women as protagonists in their own stories, instead of flighty, confused girls. <br/><br/>There isn&apos;t anything wrong with the quintessential chick lit rom-com heroine, of course - the girl who makes bad decisions, who see-saws between euphoria and manic depression depending on the amount of attention the hero pays to her, who makes us want to face palm whenever she d</span>
  <span id="freeText730592372500634782" style="display:none">Just a few pages into this book, I'd already decided that I liked the heroine, Rumi, a lot. Mainly because I love seeing <i>intelligent</i>, mature women as protagonists in their own stories, instead of flighty, confused girls. <br /><br />There isn't anything wrong with the quintessential chick lit rom-com heroine, of course - the girl who makes bad decisions, who see-saws between euphoria and manic depression depending on the amount of attention the hero pays to her, who makes us want to face palm whenever she does silly things that no sensible person should do - it's just that Rumi isn't one of these girls. And what a difference it makes. Rumi is a great protagonist because she's <i>smart</i>; you feel you'd react the same way to the situations she faces.<br /><br />The central issue of the book is a woman's right to choose the life she wants to live - free of cultural and familial restraints, a theme that will probably resonate with many South Asian women.<br /><br />The one little niggle I have is that it felt like the male protagonist, Ahad, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[was a little too quick to change his mind and propose marriage to Rumi <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. But then that's just a little nitpick that doesn't bear too deeply on the story, or the characters.<br /><br />Overall, I really enjoyed this book - a short, lovely read that flows naturally from start to finish. I never felt the need to skip, or to put the book aside; I read it in one sitting, which, to me, is the mark of a good book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="730592372500634782" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


