<div id="review_1129309452" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1129309452" />
    <a title="Fatema" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4966614-fatema"><img alt="Fatema" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1450234681p2/4966614.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1129309452?book_show_action=true">Dec 11, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fatema" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fatema" href="/user/show/4966614-fatema">Fatema</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1129309452" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15081155083722828455">Butterfly Season” by Natasha Ahmed is a light quick read. Though light and quick, it still has the depth I look for in my readings. The story revolves around the romance of Rumi and Ahad, and explores the difficulties many Desi relationships may face. Growing up in Pakistan, Rumi is torn between what she wants for herself and what her culture/society want for her.<br/><br/>The character that stood out the most, for me, is Juveria. She captures and represents the obstacles many Desi women face when going a</span>
  <span id="freeText15081155083722828455" style="display:none">Butterfly Season” by Natasha Ahmed is a light quick read. Though light and quick, it still has the depth I look for in my readings. The story revolves around the romance of Rumi and Ahad, and explores the difficulties many Desi relationships may face. Growing up in Pakistan, Rumi is torn between what she wants for herself and what her culture/society want for her.<br /><br />The character that stood out the most, for me, is Juveria. She captures and represents the obstacles many Desi women face when going against traditional expectations. The fact that the author chose to make Juveria, Rumi’s YOUNGER sister made what she represents even more perfect to me. It didn’t matter that Rumi was the older sister, Juveria still carried out her judgements against her sister because culture and tradition are thought to be stronger than family bonds.<br /><br />I enjoyed Ahmed’s style of writing and hope she continues to write more. The novella captures your attention from the beginning, and I didn’t find myself skimming pages the way I sometimes do with some books.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15081155083722828455" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


