    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1135582542" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1135582542" />
    <a title="Himaja" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7981021-himaja"><img alt="Himaja" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1330526430p2/7981021.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1135582542?book_show_action=true">Dec 19, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Himaja" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Himaja" href="/user/show/7981021-himaja">Himaja</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1135582542" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12328591785788514992">Butterfly Season by Natasha Ahmed is short, crisp and very moving. <br/><br/>When Rumi, a young woman from Karachi, visits London, she is introduced to Ahad, a very handsome Pakistani man. A whirlwind romance ensues, but soon they have to deal with different (and similar) cultural norms and expectations, and the influences of those around them. Rumi is forced to deal with the societal pressure of her &apos;inacceptable&apos; behavior in dating a man, whereas Ahad, having lived in London for many years, is expecting</span>
  <span id="freeText12328591785788514992" style="display:none">Butterfly Season by Natasha Ahmed is short, crisp and very moving. <br /><br />When Rumi, a young woman from Karachi, visits London, she is introduced to Ahad, a very handsome Pakistani man. A whirlwind romance ensues, but soon they have to deal with different (and similar) cultural norms and expectations, and the influences of those around them. Rumi is forced to deal with the societal pressure of her 'inacceptable' behavior in dating a man, whereas Ahad, having lived in London for many years, is expecting a more 'Western' style of dating prior to marriage. Through all this, Rumi finds out what her own expectations of life are. <br /><br />The storyline is a familiar one for those living in Asian cultures, and who have also been exposed to international travel and lifestyles. On one hand you get the style of living in the homeland, where dating is still taboo in most circles, unmarried girls are supposed to remain virgin and virginal, and a single girl living alone is still unheard of. On the other side of the plane is the desi lifestyle, where dating westerners is acceptable, but marriage happens only with a partner from one's own culture and background. Natasha Ahmed treads a fine line between these two cultures, giving a very graphic view of both without losing the reader in the details. <br /><br />I feel that Butterfly Season is an excellent read, which honestly and eloquently portrays the conflicts inherent in dating in Asian countries today. The choices made by the heroine remain true to her nature, and the relationship itself helps her towards introspection, to grow and to live with the choices she's made. It is a novel which uses a beautiful and idealistic romance to explore deeper issues inherent in Asian culture. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12328591785788514992" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


